reviewText: Hung was a very good show for the most part; a much more nuanced and well acted show that it's basic premise suggests. The performances are good, and the show was both touching and funny. It's evident that by season three the producers were trying to keep the show going in the face of low ratings, so the plot started to flail around quite a bit. Worst of all, the story is never wrapped up properly...you wind up having watched 30 episodes with the series ending as though it was coming back next year...which it didn't. Would have rated it 4 stares if it had ended properly, and 5 stars if it had ended well.

reviewText: The economy is bad and Ray Drecker (Thomas Jane) has lost his teaching job. What better way to make some money but to put his exceptional "asset" to work. With his friend Tanya (Jane Adams) as his pimp, Ray gets to work. The premise seemed to be losing steam by Season 3. Drecker is in his early 40's and starting to look tired and weathered. How much longer can he stay in business. Enter the conniving Lenore (Rebecca Creskoff)and a new young "escort" and his odd-ball girlfriend and the conflict continues.Ray and Tanya want to keep their business honest and simple. Tanya opens a Wellness Center for Women as a cover for Ray's services.Now the story goes in all directions. We have competing males "escorts" and more conniving and back stabbing on all sides. Ray seems to really enjoy his work and is constanting getting emotionally involved with "clients". Jealousies arise and they can only lead to disaster.Although the series is enjoyable, I was wondering what the point was. Aren't there moral implications with what Ray and Tanya are doing? Health considerations? I guess we need to overlook those questions and just follow the story. Amazingly as the season progesses, we see the show centers more around evolving personal relationships.  Ray's ex-wife (Anne Heche) is becoming more human and learning to live her own life without relying on the men in her life. Their twins have a lesser role this season. Tanya gets physically and financially involved with another pimp. Ray learns one client is not who she appears to be. In the end, this season is about the conflict between Lenore and Ray and Tanya. It can't end well as Lenore continues to scheme to be the Pimp Queen of Detroit.It's hard to imagine so many women are willing to pay $600 on an ongoing basis for Ray's services. Detroit is ecomonically depressed but you can barely tell that by this show.HBO canceled this series so we end Season 3 with cliff hangers and questions that will never be answered... just as my interest in the show was returning.A special mention should be made to Thomas Jane. I think he is one of America's underrated and underappreciated actors. I hope we see him again in other roles.
summary: QUIRKY PREMISE THAT IS LOSING STEAM

reviewText: The mark of a successful sitcom (in my opinion) is this: you've established the characters. We know each of them well. Then they become more hilarious when they pretend to be something they are clearly not. In the case of Hung, in order for their hustle to work, Ray and Tanya must do something they weren't great at previously: be professional. The pimp and the ho try to get a bank loan in the first episode to open what they call a "wellness center for women". The first class is free and it consists of Tanya pitching a lifestyle in which sex is part of your every day existence. Ray wanders into the frame towards the end of the class for the audience of women to see him after Tanya has already talked her students into feeling more aroused. But of course Lenore won't go away. Arguably the person with the best zingers in the writing, Rebecca Creskoff has the perfect comedic timing on her delivery of Tanya's nickname: "T-Brain".Fans that thought the male prostitute profession plot had limited range are wrong. Lenore finds a much younger man who perfectly compliments what Ray is not. Ray wants to embrace his job much more than previously and sees the new ho as a threat. Ann Arbor fans may appreciate the address of the artsy wellness center as 734 (area code). Ray gets more projects that involve role playing. Ray seems to almost border sex addiction. Tanya seems more desperate than Walter White (Breaking Bad). I think the writing is strong enough to give the characters much more humanity than say Californication. The nudity in Hung seems much less gratuitous.The extras (you know I gotta have my extras) are OK. I highly recommend the Alternate Ending of Episode 10. The abrupt ending to the franchise is a little easier to take if you check it out. Charles the pimp says that there are only 3 certain things in life: "Death, taxes and horny sonza bitches."
summary: Mulva? Why Season 3 Was The Best Season

reviewText: "Hung: Season 3" crosses new boundaries as male prostitute Ray Drecker (Thomas Jane) finds himself in a number of challenging client situations, yet the humanity of Ray often shines. Rival and younger male prostitute Jason (Stephen Amell), though, shows little respect to Ray and this is the cause of much drama during Season 3. Female pimp Tanya Skagle (Jane Adams) finds herself receiving the good and bad of mentor pimp Charlie's (Lennie James) advice and friendship, and his selfish antics prove a menace for her business interests and self-esteem. Season 3 contains a few notable shocks, and also some positive outcomes for a number of regular and recurring characters. Yet, for the television series to close at this point was a premature end to a show, which had at least one more good season in it.Nicholas R.W. Henning - Australian Author
summary: The third and final season, but we want more!

reviewText: After airing its 10 episode run in the fall of 2011 "Hung" was unable to hold on to its audience mainly because HBO insisted on broadcasting the series when new first-run network shows aired instead of airing it in the summer. So, sadly season 3 is the final year of one of the greatest cable shows ever produced and its the end of the road for Ray, played superbly by hunk Thomas Jane. In December, 2011 HBO officially announced it had axed "Hung".The third year continued to grow in both story content and acting as Thomas Jane proved he could be sexy, soft, rough, intelligent and manly...all attributes of the perfect guy. Ray is simply a hot property and he continues making a living being an escort for women only (unfortunately). Things really take off as Lenore, once a friend of Rays, seeks revenge against him and his pimp for stealing a business idea she had by transforming a young, hunky waiter into the next big stud on the block who works with the asset God gave him.I won't say if we do finally get to see Ray's huge "tool" this season, but it is unfortunate there are not going to be more seasons. Television doesn't get this good.There are a slew of bonuses on this two-disc set including deleted scenes,the featurette "Hung: Inside the Series", "Pimpin' Ain't Easy", the Wellness centre Walkthrough, Damon and Darby's music video, "Where Is Henry Ford?", an Alternate Ending and 4 audio commentaries.The following is a complete list of "Hung's Sason 3 episodes along with their airdates and its total viewers in millions1.
